This policy setting requires the installation of the SecGuide custom templates included with the STIG package. "SecGuide.admx" and "SecGuide.adml" must be copied to the \Windows\PolicyDefinitions and \Windows\PolicyDefinitions\en-US directories respectively.

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: IP stateless autoconfiguration limits state must be enabled.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>IP stateless autoconfiguration could configure routes that circumvent preferred routes if not limited.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls>ECSC-1</IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> Network -> TCPIP Settings -> Parameters -> "Set IP Stateless Autoconfiguration Limits State" to "Enabled".

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: Optional component installation and component repair must be prevented from using Windows Update.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>Uncontrolled system updates can introduce issues to a system. Obtaining update components from an outside source may also potentially provide sensitive information outside of the enterprise. Optional component installation or repair must be obtained from an internal source.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls>ECSC-1</IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> System -> "Specify settings for optional component installation and component repair" to "Enabled" and with "Never attempt to download payload from Windows Update" selected.

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: Device driver updates must only search managed servers, not Windows Update.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>Uncontrolled system updates can introduce issues to a system. Obtaining update components from an outside source may also potentially provide sensitive information outside of the enterprise. Device driver updates must be obtained from an internal source.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls>ECSC-1</IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> System -> Device Installation -> "Specify the search server for device driver updates" to "Enabled" with "Search Managed Server" selected.

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: Early Launch Antimalware, Boot-Start Driver Initialization Policy must be enabled and configured to only Good and Unknown.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>Compromised boot drivers can introduce malware prior to some protection mechanisms that load after initialization. The Early Launch Antimalware driver can limit allowed drivers based on classifications determined by the malware protection application. At a minimum, drivers determined to be bad must not be allowed.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls>ECVP-1</IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> System -> Early Launch Antimalware -> "Boot-Start Driver Initialization Policy" to "Enabled" with "Good and Unknown" selected.

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: Access to the Windows Store must be turned off.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>Uncontrolled installation of applications can introduce various issues, including system instability, and allow access to sensitive information. Installation of applications must be controlled by the enterprise. Turning off access to the Windows Store will limit access to publicly available applications.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls></IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext:
If the \Windows\WinStore directory exists, configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> System >> Internet Communication Management >> Internet Communication settings >> "Turn off access to the Store" to "Enabled".
Alternately, uninstall the "Desktop Experience" feature from Windows 2012. This is located under "User Interfaces and Infrastructure" in the "Add Roles and Features Wizard". The \Windows\WinStore directory may need to be manually deleted after this.

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: Copying of user input methods to the system account for sign-in must be prevented.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>Allowing different input methods for sign-in could open different avenues of attack. User input methods must be restricted to those enabled for the system account at sign-in.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls>ECSC-1</IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> System -> Locale Services -> "Disallow copying of user input methods to the system account for sign-in" to "Enabled".

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: Local users on domain-joined computers must not be enumerated.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>The username is one part of logon credentials that could be used to gain access to a system. Preventing the enumeration of users limits this information to authorized personnel.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls>ECSC-1</IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> System -> Logon -> "Enumerate local users on domain-joined computers" to "Disabled".

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: App notifications on the lock screen must be turned off.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>App notifications that are displayed on the lock screen could display sensitive information to unauthorized personnel. Turning off this feature will limit access to the information to a logged on user.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls>ECSC-1</IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> System -> Logon -> "Turn off app notifications on the lock screen" to "Enabled".

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: The detection of compatibility issues for applications and drivers must be turned off.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>Some features may communicate with the vendor, sending system information or downloading data or components for the feature. Turning off this feature will prevent potentially sensitive information from being sent outside the enterprise and uncontrolled updates to the system.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls></IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> System -> Troubleshooting and Diagnostics -> Application Compatibility Diagnostics -> "Detect compatibility issues for applications and drivers" to "Disabled".

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: Trusted app installation must be enabled to allow for signed enterprise line of business apps.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>Enabling trusted app installation allows for enterprise line of business Windows 8 type apps. A trusted app package is one that is signed with a certificate chain that can be successfully validated in the enterprise. Configuring this ensures enterprise line of business apps are accessible.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls>ECSC-1</IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> Windows Components -> App Package Deployment -> "Allow all trusted apps to install" to "Enabled".

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: The use of biometrics must be disabled.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>Allowing biometrics may bypass required authentication methods. Biometrics may only be used as an additional authentication factor where an enhanced strength of identity credential is necessary or desirable. Additional factors must be met per DoD policy.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls>IAIA-1</IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> Windows Components -> Biometrics -> "Allow the use of biometrics" to "Disabled".

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: The password reveal button must not be displayed.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>Visible passwords may be seen by nearby persons, compromising them. The password reveal button can be used to display an entered password and must not be allowed.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls>IAIA-1</IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> Windows Components -> Credential User Interface -> "Do not display the password reveal button" to "Enabled".

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: Windows SmartScreen must be enabled on Windows 2012/2012 R2.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>Windows SmartScreen helps protect systems from programs downloaded from the Internet that may be malicious. Warning a user before running downloaded unknown software, at minimum, will help prevent potentially malicious programs from executing.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls></IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext:
Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> File Explorer >> "Configure Windows SmartScreen" to "Enabled" with either "Give user a warning before running downloaded unknown software" or "Require approval from an administrator before running downloaded unknown software" selected.
Microsoft has changed this setting several times in the Windows 10 administrative templates, which will affect group policies in a domain if later templates are used.
v1607 of Windows 10 and Windows Server 2016 changed the setting to only Enabled or Disabled without additional selections. Enabled is effectively "Give user a warning...".
v1703 of Windows 10 or later administrative templates changed the policy name to "Configure Windows Defender SmartScreen", and the selectable options are "Warn" and "Warn and prevent bypass". When either of these are applied to a Windows 2012/2012 R2 system, it will configure the registry equivalent of "Give user a warning...").

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: The location feature must be turned off.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>The location service on systems may allow sensitive data to be used by applications on the system. This should be turned off unless explicitly allowed for approved systems/applications.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls></IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext:
Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> Windows Components -> Location and Sensors -> "Turn off location" to "Enabled".
If location services are approved by the organization for a device, this must be documented.

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: Basic authentication for RSS feeds over HTTP must be turned off.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>Basic authentication uses plain text passwords that could be used to compromise a system.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls>ECSC-1</IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> Windows Components -> RSS Feeds -> "Turn on Basic feed authentication over HTTP" to "Disabled".

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: The Windows Remote Management (WinRM) client must not use Basic authentication.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>Basic authentication uses plain text passwords that could be used to compromise a system.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls>IAIA-1</IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> Windows Components -> Windows Remote Management (WinRM) -> WinRM Client -> "Allow Basic authentication" to "Disabled".

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: The Windows Remote Management (WinRM) client must not allow unencrypted traffic.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>Unencrypted remote access to a system can allow sensitive information to be compromised. Windows remote management connections must be encrypted to prevent this.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls></IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> Windows Components -> Windows Remote Management (WinRM) -> WinRM Client -> "Allow unencrypted traffic" to "Disabled".

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: The Windows Remote Management (WinRM) client must not use Digest authentication.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>Digest authentication is not as strong as other options and may be subject to man-in-the-middle attacks.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls>IAIA-1</IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> Windows Components -> Windows Remote Management (WinRM) -> WinRM Client -> "Disallow Digest authentication" to "Enabled".

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: The Windows Remote Management (WinRM) service must not use Basic authentication.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>Basic authentication uses plain text passwords that could be used to compromise a system.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls></IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> Windows Components -> Windows Remote Management (WinRM) -> WinRM Service -> "Allow Basic authentication" to "Disabled".

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: The Windows Remote Management (WinRM) service must not allow unencrypted traffic.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>Unencrypted remote access to a system can allow sensitive information to be compromised. Windows remote management connections must be encrypted to prevent this.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls></IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> Windows Components -> Windows Remote Management (WinRM) -> WinRM Service -> "Allow unencrypted traffic" to "Disabled".

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: The Windows Remote Management (WinRM) service must not store RunAs credentials.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>Storage of administrative credentials could allow unauthorized access. Disallowing the storage of RunAs credentials for Windows Remote Management will prevent them from being used with plug-ins.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls>ECLP-1</IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Administrative Templates -> Windows Components -> Windows Remote Management (WinRM) -> WinRM Service -> "Disallow WinRM from storing RunAs credentials" to "Enabled".

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: The machine inactivity limit must be set to 15 minutes, locking the system with the screensaver.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>Unattended systems are susceptible to unauthorized use and should be locked when unattended. The screen saver should be set at a maximum of 15 minutes and be password protected. This protects critical and sensitive data from exposure to unauthorized personnel with physical access to the computer.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls></IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Windows Settings -> Security Settings -> Local Policies -> Security Options -> "Interactive logon: Machine inactivity limit" to "900" seconds" or less, excluding "0" which is effectively disabled.

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: The Smart Card Removal Policy service must be configured to automatic.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>The automatic start of the Smart Card Removal Policy service is required to support the smart card removal behavior requirement.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls>ECSC-1</IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the Startup Type for the Smart Card Removal Policy service to "Automatic".

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: The US DoD CCEB Interoperability Root CA cross-certificates must be installed into the Untrusted Certificates Store on unclassified systems.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>To ensure users do not experience denial of service when performing certificate-based authentication to DoD websites due to the system chaining to a root other than DoD Root CAs, the US DoD CCEB Interoperability Root CA cross-certificates must be installed in the Untrusted Certificate Store. This requirement only applies to unclassified systems.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls></IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext:
Install the US DoD CCEB Interoperability Root CA cross-certificate on unclassified systems.
Issued To - Issued By - Thumbprint DoD Root CA 3 - US DoD CCEB Interoperability Root CA 2 - 929BF3196896994C0A201DF4A5B71F603FEFBF2E
The certificates can be installed using the InstallRoot tool. The tool and user guide are available on IASE at http://iase.disa.mil/pki-pke/Pages/tools.aspx.

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: Windows 2012 R2 must include command line data in process creation events.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description:
<VulnDiscussion>Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.
Enabling "Include command line data for process creation events" will record the command line information with the process creation events in the log. This can provide additional detail when malware has run on a system.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls></IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> System >> Audit Process Creation >> "Include command line in process creation events" to "Enabled".

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: The system must be configured to audit Policy Change - Authorization Policy Change successes.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description:
<VulnDiscussion>Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.
Authorization Policy Change records events related to changes in user rights, such as Create a token object.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls></IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Windows Settings -> Security Settings -> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration -> System Audit Policies -> Policy Change -> "Audit Authorization Policy Change" with "Success" selected.

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: Users must be required to enter a password to access private keys stored on the computer.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description:
<VulnDiscussion>If the private key is discovered, an attacker can use the key to authenticate as an authorized user and gain access to the network infrastructure.
The cornerstone of the PKI is the private key used to encrypt or digitally sign information.
If the private key is stolen, this will lead to the compromise of the authentication and non-repudiation gained through PKI because the attacker can use the private key to digitally sign documents and pretend to be the authorized user.
Both the holders of a digital certificate and the issuing authority must protect the computers, storage devices, or whatever they use to keep the private keys.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls></IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> Security Options >> "System cryptography: Force strong key protection for user keys stored on the computer" to "User must enter a password each time they use a key".

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: Event Viewer must be protected from unauthorized modification and deletion.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description:
<VulnDiscussion>Protecting audit information also includes identifying and protecting the tools used to view and manipulate log data. Therefore, protecting audit tools is necessary to prevent unauthorized operation on audit information.
Operating systems providing tools to interface with audit information will leverage user permissions and roles identifying the user accessing the tools and the corresponding rights the user enjoys in order to make access decisions regarding the modification or deletion of audit tools.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls></IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext:
Ensure only TrustedInstaller has permissions to change or modify Event Viewer ("%SystemRoot%\SYSTEM32\Eventvwr.exe).
The default permissions below satisfy this requirement. TrustedInstaller - Full Control Administrators, SYSTEM, Users, ALL APPLICATION PACKAGES - Read & Execute

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: The Server Message Block (SMB) v1 protocol must be disabled on the SMB server.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description:
<VulnDiscussion>SMBv1 is a legacy protocol that uses the MD5 algorithm as part of SMB. MD5 is known to be vulnerable to a number of attacks such as collision and preimage attacks as well as not being FIPS compliant.
Disabling SMBv1 support may prevent access to file or print sharing resources with systems or devices that only support SMBv1. File shares and print services hosted on Windows Server 2003 are an example, however Windows Server 2003 is no longer a supported operating system. Some older network attached devices may only support SMBv1.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls></IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext:
Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> MS Security Guide >> "Configure SMBv1 Server" to "Disabled".
The system must be restarted for the change to take effect.
This policy setting requires the installation of the SecGuide custom templates included with the STIG package. "SecGuide.admx" and "SecGuide.adml" must be copied to the \Windows\PolicyDefinitions and \Windows\PolicyDefinitions\en-US directories respectively.

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: The Server Message Block (SMB) v1 protocol must be disabled on the SMB client.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description:
<VulnDiscussion>SMBv1 is a legacy protocol that uses the MD5 algorithm as part of SMB. MD5 is known to be vulnerable to a number of attacks such as collision and preimage attacks as well as not being FIPS compliant.
Disabling SMBv1 support may prevent access to file or print sharing resources with systems or devices that only support SMBv1. File shares and print services hosted on Windows Server 2003 are an example, however Windows Server 2003 is no longer a supported operating system. Some older network attached devices may only support SMBv1.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls></IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext:
Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> MS Security Guide >> "Configure SMBv1 client driver" to "Enabled" with "Disable driver (recommended)" selected for "Configure MrxSmb10 driver".
Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> MS Security Guide >> "Configure SMBv1 client (extra setting needed for pre-Win8.1/2012R2)" to "Enabled" with the following three lines of text entered for "Configure LanmanWorkstation Dependencies": Bowser MRxSmb20 NSI
The system must be restarted for the changes to take effect.
These policy settings requires the installation of the SecGuide custom templates included with the STIG package. "SecGuide.admx" and "SecGuide.adml" must be copied to the \Windows\PolicyDefinitions and \Windows\PolicyDefinitions\en-US directories respectively.

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: The Server Message Block (SMB) v1 protocol must be disabled on Windows 2012 R2.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description:
<VulnDiscussion>SMBv1 is a legacy protocol that uses the MD5 algorithm as part of SMB. MD5 is known to be vulnerable to a number of attacks such as collision and preimage attacks as well as not being FIPS compliant.
Disabling SMBv1 support may prevent access to file or print sharing resources with systems or devices that only support SMBv1. File shares and print services hosted on Windows Server 2003 are an example, however Windows Server 2003 is no longer a supported operating system. Some older network attached devices may only support SMBv1.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls></IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext:
Run "Windows PowerShell" with elevated privileges (run as administrator). Enter the following: Disable-WindowsOptionalFeature -Online -FeatureName SMB1Protocol
Alternately: Search for "Features". Select "Turn Windows features on or off". De-select "SMB 1.0/CIFS File Sharing Support".
The system must be restarted for the changes to take effect.

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: Windows Server 2012/2012 R2 must be configured to audit Logon/Logoff - Account Lockout successes.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description:
<VulnDiscussion>Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.
Account Lockout events can be used to identify potentially malicious logon attempts. </VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls></IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Logon/Logoff >> "Audit Account Lockout" with "Success" selected.

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: Windows Server 2012/2012 R2 must be configured to audit Logon/Logoff - Account Lockout failures.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description:
<VulnDiscussion>Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.
Account Lockout events can be used to identify potentially malicious logon attempts.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls></IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Logon/Logoff >> "Audit Account Lockout" with "Failure" selected.

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: Windows Server 2012/2012 R2 must be configured to audit System - Other System Events successes.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description:
<VulnDiscussion>Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.
Audit Other System Events records information related to cryptographic key operations and the Windows Firewall service.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls></IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> System >> "Audit Other System Events" with "Success" selected.

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: Windows Server 2012/2012 R2 must be configured to audit System - Other System Events failures.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description:
<VulnDiscussion>Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.
Audit Other System Events records information related to cryptographic key operations and the Windows Firewall service.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls></IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext: Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> System >> "Audit Other System Events" with "Failure" selected.

cdf12:Rule.cdf12:title: Windows PowerShell 2.0 must not be installed on Windows 2012/2012 R2.
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:description: <VulnDiscussion>Windows PowerShell versions 4.0 (with a patch) and 5.x add advanced logging features that can provide additional detail when malware has been run on a system. Ensuring Windows PowerShell 2.0 is not installed as well mitigates against a downgrade attack that evades the advanced logging features of later Windows PowerShell versions.</VulnDiscussion><FalsePositives></FalsePositives><FalseNegatives></FalseNegatives><Documentable>false</Documentable><Mitigations></Mitigations><SeverityOverrideGuidance></SeverityOverrideGuidance><PotentialImpacts></PotentialImpacts><ThirdPartyTools></ThirdPartyTools><MitigationControl></MitigationControl><Responsibility></Responsibility><IAControls></IAControls>
cdf12:Rule.cdf12:fixtext:
Windows PowerShell 2.0 is not installed by default.
Uninstall it if it has been installed.
Open "Windows PowerShell".
Enter "Uninstall-WindowsFeature -Name PowerShell-v2".
Alternately:
Use the "Remove Roles and Features Wizard" and deselect "Windows PowerShell 2.0 Engine" under "Windows PowerShell".

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Lockout Duration
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Windows 2012 account lockout duration must be configured to 15 minutes or greater.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Account lockout duration' is set to '0'
Verifies 'Account lockout threshold' is not set to '0'
Verifies 'Account lockout duration' is set to '15 or greater'
Verifies 'Account lockout threshold' is not set to '0'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Bad Logon Attempts
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The number of allowed bad logon attempts must meet minimum requirements.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Account lockout threshold' is set to '3' or less
Verifies 'Account lockout threshold' is not set to '0'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Bad Logon Counter Reset
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Windows 2012 must be configured for the period of time before the bad logon counter is reset to 15 minutes or greater.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Reset account lockout counter after' is set to at least '15' minutes
Verifies 'Account lockout threshold' is not set to '0'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Password Uniqueness
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Password uniqueness must meet minimum requirements.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Enforce password history' is set to '5' passwords or more

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Maximum Password Age
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Maximum password age must meet minimum requirements.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Maximum Password Age' is set to '60' days or less
Verifies 'Maximum Password Age' is not set to '0'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Minimum Password Age
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The minimum password age must meet requirements.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Minimum Password Age' is set to at least '1' day

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Minimum Password Length
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Passwords must, at a minimum, be 14 characters.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Minimum password length' is set to at least '14' characters

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Microsoft Strong Password Filtering
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The built-in Microsoft password complexity filter must be enabled.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Password must meet complexity requirements' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Reversible Password Encryption
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Reversible password encryption must be disabled.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Store password using reversible encryption' is set to 'Disabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Network - Mapper I/O Driver
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The Mapper I/O network protocol (LLTDIO) driver must be disabled.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies AllowLLTDIOOnDomain value equals 0
Verifies AllowLLTDIOOnPublicNet value equals 0
Verifies EnableLLTDIO value equals 0
Verifies ProhibitLLTDIOOnPrivateNet value equals 0

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Network - Responder Driver
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The Responder network protocol driver must be disabled.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies AllowRspndrOnDomain value equals 0
Verifies AllowRspndrOnPublicNet value equals 0
Verifies EnableRspndr value equals 0
Verifies ProhibitRspndrOnPrivateNet value equals 0

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Windows Peer to Peer Networking
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Windows Peer-to-Peer networking services must be turned off.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Turn Off Microsoft Peer-to-Peer Networking Services' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Prohibit Network Bridge
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Network Bridges must be prohibited in Windows.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Prohibit installation and configuration of Network Bridge on your DNS domain network' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Elevate when setting a networks location
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Domain users must be required to elevate when setting a networks location.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Require domain users to elevate when setting a network's location' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Direct Access - Route Through Internal Network
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: All Direct Access traffic must be routed through the internal network.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Route all traffic through the internal network' is set to 'Enabled: Enabled State'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: 6to4 State
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The 6to4 IPv6 transition technology must be disabled.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Set 6to4 State' is set to 'Enabled: Disabled State'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: IP-HTTPS State
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The IP-HTTPS IPv6 transition technology must be disabled.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'IP-HTTPS URL:' is not null
Verifies 'IP-HTTPS State' is set to 'Enabled: Disabled State'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: ISATAP State
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The ISATAP IPv6 transition technology must be disabled.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'ISATAP State' is set to 'Enabled: Disabled State'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Teredo State
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The Teredo IPv6 transition technology must be disabled.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Teredo State' is set to 'Enabled: Disabled State'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Network - WCN Wireless Configuration
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The configuration of wireless devices using Windows Connect Now must be disabled.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies DisableInBand802DOT11Registrar value equals 0
Verifies DisableFlashConfigRegistrar value equals 0
Verifies DisableUPnPRegistrar value equals 0
Verifies DisableWPDRegistrar value equals 0
Verifies EnableRegistrars value equals 0

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Network - Windows Connect Now Wizards
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The Windows Connect Now wizards must be disabled.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Prohibit Access of the Windows Connect Now wizards' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Windows Update Point and Print Driver Search
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Windows Update must be prevented from searching for point and print drivers.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Extend Point and Print connection to search Windows Update' is set to 'Disabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: WINCC-000018
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Optional component installation and component repair must be prevented from using Windows Update.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Specify settings for optional component installation and component repair' is set to 'Enabled' with 'Never attempt to download payload from Windows Update' selected

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Device Install - PnP Interface Remote Access
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Remote access to the Plug and Play interface must be disabled for device installation.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Allow remote access to the Plug and Play interface' is set to 'Disabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Device Install - Generic Driver Error Report
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: An Error Report must not be sent when a generic device driver is installed.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Do not send a Windows error report when a generic driver is installed on a device' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Device Install - Drivers System Restore Point
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: A system restore point must be created when a new device driver is installed.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Prevent creation of a system restore point during device activity that would normally prompt creation of a restore point' is set to 'Disabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Prevent device metadata retrieval from Internet
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Device metadata retrieval from the Internet must be prevented.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Prevent device metadata retrieval from the Internet' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Device Install Software Request Error Report
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Windows must be prevented from sending an error report when a device driver requests additional software during installation.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Prevent Windows from sending an error report when a device driver requests additional software during installation' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Prevent Windows Update for device driver search
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Device driver searches using Windows Update must be prevented.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Specify search order for device driver source locations' is set to 'Enabled: Do not search Windows Update'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: WINCC-000025
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Device driver updates must only search managed servers, not Windows Update.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Specify the search server for device driver updates' is set to 'Enabled' with 'Search Managed Server' selected

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Driver Install - Device Driver Search Prompt
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Users must not be prompted to search Windows Update for device drivers.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Turn off Windows Update device driver search prompt' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: WINCC-000027
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Early Launch Antimalware, Boot-Start Driver Initialization Policy must be enabled and configured to only Good and Unknown.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Boot-Start Driver Initialization Policy' is set to 'Enabled' with 'Good and Unknown' selected

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Group Policy objects must be reprocessed even if they have not changed.
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Enabling this setting and then selecting the "Process even if the Group Policy objects have not changed" option ensures that the policies will be reprocessed even if none have been changed. This way, any unauthorized changes are forced to match the domain-based group policy settings again.

oval-def:criterion.comment: NoGPOListChanges is set to 0.

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: WINCC-000030
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Access to the Windows Store must be turned off.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Windows\WinStore does not exist, Not Applicable
Verifies 'Turn off access to the Store' is set to 'Enabled'
Windows\WinStore exist

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: HTTP Printer Drivers
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Downloading print driver packages over HTTP must be prevented.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Turn off downloading of print drivers over HTTP' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Handwriting Recognition Error Reporting
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Errors in handwriting recognition on Tablet PCs must not be reported to Microsoft.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Turn off handwriting recognition error reporting' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Internet File Association Service
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The Internet File Association service must be turned off.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Turn off Internet File Association service' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Printing Over HTTP
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Printing over HTTP must be prevented.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Turn off printing over HTTP' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Windows Customer Experience Improvement Program
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The Windows Customer Experience Improvement Program must be disabled.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Turn off Windows Customer Experience Improvement Program' is set to 'Disabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Windows Update Device Drive Searching
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Windows must be prevented from using Windows Update to search for drivers.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Turn off Windows Update device driver searching' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: WINCC-000048
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Copying of user input methods to the system account for sign-in must be prevented.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Disallow copying of user input methods to the system account for sign-in' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: WINCC-000051
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Local users on domain-joined computers must not be enumerated.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Enumerate local users on domain-joined computers' is set to 'Disabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: WINCC-000052
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: App notifications on the lock screen must be turned off.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Turn off app notifications on the lock screen' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Power Mgmt - Password Wake on Battery
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Users must be prompted for a password on resume from sleep (on battery).

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Require a password when a computer wakes (on battery)' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Power Mgmt - Password Wake When Plugged In
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The user must be prompted for a password on resume from sleep (plugged in).

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Require a password when a computer wakes (plugged in)' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Remote Assistance - Offer Remote Assistance
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The system must be configured to prevent unsolicited remote assistance offers.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Configure Offer Remote Assistance' is set to 'Disabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Remote Assistance - Solicit Remote Assistance
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Solicited Remote Assistance must not be allowed.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Configure Solicited Remote Assistance' is set to 'Disabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Remote Assistance - Session Logging
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Remote Assistance log files must be generated.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Turn on session logging' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: RPC - Unauthenticated RPC Clients
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Unauthenticated RPC clients must be restricted from connecting to the RPC server.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Restrict Unauthenticated RPC clients' is set to 'Enabled' and 'Authenticated'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: WINCC-000065
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The detection of compatibility issues for applications and drivers must be turned off.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Detect compatibility issues for applications and drivers' is set to 'Disabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: MSDT Interactive Communication
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Microsoft Support Diagnostic Tool (MSDT) interactive communication with Microsoft must be prevented.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Microsoft Support Diagnostic Tool: Turn on MSDT interactive communication with Support Provider' is set to 'Disabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Windows Online Troubleshooting Service
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Access to Windows Online Troubleshooting Service (WOTS) must be prevented.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Troubleshooting: Allow users to access online troubleshooting content on Microsoft servers from the Troubleshooting Control Panel (via Windows Online Troubleshooting Service - WOTS)' is set to 'Disabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Disable PerfTrack
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Responsiveness events must be prevented from being aggregated and sent to Microsoft.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Enable/Disable PerfTrack' is set to 'Disabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: WINCC-000070
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Trusted app installation must be enabled to allow for signed enterprise line of business apps.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Allow all trusted apps to install' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Application Compatibility Program Inventory
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The Application Compatibility Program Inventory must be prevented from collecting data and sending the information to Microsoft.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Turn off Inventory Collector' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Autoplay for non-volume devices
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Autoplay must be turned off for non-volume devices.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Disallow Autoplay for non-volume devices' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Default Autorun Behavior
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The default autorun behavior must be configured to prevent autorun commands.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Default behavior for AutoRun' is set to 'Enabled:Do not execute any autorun commands'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Disable Media Autoplay
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Autoplay must be disabled for all drives.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Turn off AutoPlay' is set to 'Enabled:All Drives'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: WINCC-000075
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The use of biometrics must be disabled.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Detect compatibility issues for applications and drivers' is set to 'Disabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: WINCC-000076
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The password reveal button must not be displayed.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Do not display the password reveal button' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Enumerate Administrator Accounts on Elevation
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The system must require username and password to elevate a running application.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Enumerate administrator accounts on elevation' is set to 'Disabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Maximum Log Size - Application
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The Application event log must be configured to a minimum size requirement.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Specify the maximum log size (KB)' is set at a minimum to 'Enabled:32768'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Maximum Log Size - Security
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The Security event log size must be configured to 196608 KB or greater.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Specify the maximum log size (KB)' is set at a minimum to 'Enabled:196608'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Maximum Log Size - Setup
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The Setup event log must be configured to a minimum size requirement.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Specify the maximum log size (KB)' is set at a minimum to 'Enabled:32768'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Maximum Log Size - System
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The System event log must be configured to a minimum size requirement.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Specify the maximum log size (KB)' is set at a minimum to 'Enabled:32768'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: WN12-CC-000088
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The Windows SmartScreen must be enabled on Windows 2012/2012 R2.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Configure Windows SmartScreen' is set to 'Enabled' with 'Give user a warning...' selected or 'Require approval from an administrator...' selected

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Explorer Data Execution Prevention
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Explorer Data Execution Prevention must be enabled.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Turn off Data Execution Prevention for Explorer' is set to 'Disabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Windows Explorer - Heap Termination
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Turning off File Explorer heap termination on corruption must be disabled.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Turn off heap termination on corruption' is set to 'Disabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Windows Explorer - Shell Protocol Protected Mode
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: File Explorer shell protocol must run in protected mode.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Turn off shell protocol protected mode' is set to 'Disabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: WINCC-000095
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The location feature must be turned off.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Turn off location' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: TS/RDS - Prevent Password Saving
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Passwords must not be saved in the Remote Desktop Client.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Do not allow passwords to be saved' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: TS/RDS - Drive Redirection

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Do not allow drive redirection' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: TS/RDS - Set Encryption Level

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: TS/RDS - Delete Temp Folders

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: TS/RDS - Do Not Use Temp Folders

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Do not use temporary folders per session' is set to 'Disabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: RSS Attachment Downloads
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Attachments must be prevented from being downloaded from RSS feeds.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Prevent downloading of enclosures' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Windows Installer - User Control

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Enable user control over installs' is set to 'Disabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Always Install with Elevated Privileges Disabled
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: The Windows Installer Always install with elevated privileges must be disabled.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Always install with elevated privileges' is set to 'Disabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Windows Installer - IE Security Prompt
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Users must be notified if a web-based program attempts to install software.

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: Windows Installer - Vendor Signed Updates
oval-def:metadata.oval-def:description: Non-administrators must be prevented from applying vendor-signed updates.

oval-def:criterion.comment: Verifies 'Prohibit non-administrators from applying vendor signed updates' is set to 'Enabled'

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: WINCC-000125

oval-def:metadata.oval-def:title: WINCC-000127

Verifies the OS Build is equal to or greater than 9200
